The paper deals with parameterized algorithms for graph problems, specifically Steiner Tree and Subset TSP, in the context of planar graphs. This suggests that the paper could belong to several arXiv CS sub-categories, including cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), cs.CG (computational geometry), cs.DM (discrete mathematics), cs.CC (computational complexity), and cs.GT (graph theory). However, given the focus on parameterized algorithms and graph problems, cs.DS and cs.CG seem to be the most likely categories. The use of planar graphs also suggests cs.CG as a likely category, as planarity is a key concept in computational geometry. The paper's results on the complexity of Steiner Tree and Subset TSP also suggest cs.CC and cs.GT as possible categories, as these are classic graph problems that are of interest to researchers in these areas. Finally, the use of exponential-time hypotheses in the paper suggests cs.DM as a possible category, as this is an area of research that deals with the study of the complexity of algorithms and problems.
